.TH "CSSKEYFRAMERULE.STYLE" "3JS" "November 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
CSSKeyframeRule.style \- CSSKeyframeRule: style property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]style\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]CSSKeyframeRule\f[R] interface contains a
\f[CR]CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R] object representing the descriptors
available in the \f[CR]\(atkeyframes\f[R] rule\(cqs body.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R] object.
.PP
Although the \f[CR]style\f[R] property itself is read\-only in the sense
that you can\(cqt replace the \f[CR]CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R] object, you
can still assign to the \f[CR]style\f[R] property directly, which is
equivalent to assigning to its \f[CR]cssText\f[R] property.
You can also modify the \f[CR]CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R] object using the
\f[CR]setProperty()\f[R] and \f[CR]removeProperty()\f[R] methods.
.SH EXAMPLES
The CSS includes a \f[CR]\(atkeyframes\f[R] at\-rule.
This will be the first \f[CR]CSSRule\f[R] returned by
\f[CR]document.styleSheets[0].cssRules\f[R].
\f[CR]myRules[0]\f[R] returns a \f[CR]CSSKeyframesRule\f[R] object,
which will contain individual \f[CR]CSSKeyFrameRule\f[R] objects for
each keyframe.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\(atkeyframes\f[R] slide\-in {
  from {
    \f[B]transform\f[R]: translateX(0%);
  }

  to {
    \f[B]transform\f[R]: translateX(100%);
  }
}
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] myRules = document.styleSheets[0].cssRules;
\f[B]let\f[R] keyframes = myRules[0]; \f[I]// a CSSKeyframesRule\f[R]
console.log(keyframes[0].style); \f[I]// a CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R]
.EE
